include ../../tlMatter.pug
if docLang === "EN"
  mixin tl(tlText)
    if tlText != null
      +inlineTl("EN", tlText)
    else
      +inlineTl("EN")
        block
    
  mixin tlDb(key)
    case key
      when "teidealNaCaibidle"
        | The Copula
      when "7-1-title"
        | General
      when "7-title"
        | #[+renderKey("Caibidil", { getFromCommon: true })] 7 | #[+renderKey("teidealNaCaibidle")]
      when "7-1-p1"
        | The copula is used to link two words or two phrases together.
      when "7-1-p2"
        | The form of the copula used in the present tense is the same as that used in the future tense. Moreover, the form of the copula, when used in the past tense, the past habitual tense, and the conditional mood, is the same. Bear in mind, if the predicate of the sentence is in the past tense, the present tense, or the conditional mood, the tense of the copula and the tense of the predicate would not necessarily agree with each other. See #[+link("#sec_7_2", "7.2")] for simple forms of the copula.
      when "7-1-1-title"
        | Functions of the Copula
      when "7-1-1-p"
        | The primary functions of the copula are &mdash;
        | #[br]
        | (#[b TL Note]: The copula does not always translate directly, so no attempt will be made to parallel.)
      when "7-1-1-a-p"
        | classification of the subject:
      when "7-1-1-a-sample1"
        | She is an excellent actor.
      when "7-1-1-a-sample2"
        | The seagull is a bird.
      when "7-1-1-a-sample3"
        | They are strangers.
      when "7-1-1-a-sample4"
        | He is a man.
      when "7-1-1-b-p"
        | identification of the subject:
      when "7-1-1-b-sample1"
        | Úna was the manager.
      when "7-1-1-b-sample2"
        | Dublin is the capital of Ireland.
      when "7-1-1-c-p"
        | qualification of the subject with a predicate adjective or with a phrase starting with a preposition:
      when "7-1-1-c-sample1"
        | Isn&rsquo;t it nice?
      when "7-1-1-c-sample2"
        | That is true.
      when "7-1-1-c-sample3"
        | Five Euro is enough.
      when "7-1-1-c-sample4"
        | She is from Mullingar.
      when "7-1-1-d-p"
        | qualification of a noun or clause, or with a noun plus a prepositional pronominal:
      when "7-1-1-d-sample1"
        | She likes basketball.
      when "7-1-1-d-sample2"
        | He must leave.
      when "7-1-1-d-sample3"
        | Can he do it?
      when "7-1-1-d-sample4"
        | That is enough for me.
      when "7-1-1-d-sample5"
        | Do you remember that house?
      when "7-1-1-d-sample6"
        | We are sorry for this break.
      when "7-1-1-e-p"
        | qualification of a noun with a comparative adjective:
      when "7-1-1-e-sample1"
        | Take the one you like best.
      when "7-1-1-e-sample2"
        | The nicest sweets were eaten before I arrived at the party.
      when "7-1-1-f-p"
        | expression of ownership or relationship between people using the preposition #[i le]:
      when "7-1-1-f-sample1"
        | It was mine.
      when "7-1-1-f-sample2"
        | That one is not Sorcha&rsquo;s.
      when "7-1-1-f-sample3"
        | Take any one you like.
      when "7-1-1-f-sample4"
        | She is Seán&rsquo;s daughter.
      when "7-1-1-f-sample5"
        | He is Cáit&rsquo;s colleague.
      when "7-1-1-g-p"
        | qualification of a clause with an adjective:
      when "7-1-1-g-sample1"
        | Soon we will know.
      when "7-1-1-g-sample2"
        | It has been a long time since he was there.
      when "7-1-1-g-sample3"
        | You know it well.
      when "7-1-1-g-sample4"
        | Many people come this way.
      when "7-1-1-g-sample5"
        | He was a long time coming.
      when "7-1-1-h-p"
        | emphasizing part of the sentence:
      when "7-1-1-h-sample1"
        | He was not born today or yesterday.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample2"
        | I was buying milk.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample3"
        | It was to Spain she went.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample4"
        | It was not Muireann that lost the key.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample5"
        | Nóra translated that.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample6"
        | She was right.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample7"
        | That was not the kind of competition that was there in 1998.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample8"
        | Yesterday they came.
      when "7-1-1-h-sample9"
        | Peadar would make the move if he were here.
      when "7-1-1-i-p"
        | using it in sentences that express a comparison:
      when "7-1-1-i-sample1"
        | A twopence is heavier than a penny.
      when "7-1-1-i-sample2"
        | The sun is brighter than either the moon or the planets.
      when "7-1-1-i-sample3"
        | Countries aren&rsquo;t more numerous than customs. (#[i figuratively: so many men, so many minds])
      when "7-1-1-i-sample4"
        | Isn&rsquo;t nature stronger than nurture?
      when "7-1-1-i-sample5"
        | Wouldn&rsquo;t a car be better than a bicycle?
      when "7-2-title"
        | Simple Forms of the Copula and Initial Mutation
      when "7-2-a-p"
        | A simple form is a form of the copula that is not composed with an interrogative pronominal, preposition or conjunction.
      when "7-2-b-p1"
        | The simple forms of copula are given here:
      when "7-2-b-i-p"
        | in a main clause;
      when "7-2-b-ii-p"
        | at the beginning of a subordinate clause, rather than a relative clause;
      when "7-2-b-iii-p"
        | in a direct relative clause;
      when "7-2-b-iv-p"
        | in an indirect relative clause.
      when "7-2-b-p2"
        | The forms are refined by their tense. In each situation, the present tense and the future tense are given first followed by the past tense, the past habitual tense and the conditional mood.
      when "7-2-1-title"
        | Simple Forms in Main Clauses
      when "7-2-1-A-title"
        | The Present Tense and The Future Tense
      when "7-2-1-A-p"
        | The following table lays out the positive form, the negative form, the positive interrogative form and the negative interrogative form of the copula in the present tense or the future tense.
      when "Table7A-caption"
        | Simple Forms in Main Clauses &mdash; The Present Tense and Future Tense
      when "Table7A-header"
        | The Present Tense and Future Tense
      when "Table7A-subheader"
        | before every consonant and every vowel
      when "Table7A-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i It is good land now.]
      when "Table7A-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i She is a good artist.]
      when "Table7A-example3"
        | #[b EN]: #[i It is not milk, and it is not buttermilk.]
      when "Table7A-example4"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He is not the one who told that lie.]
      when "Table7A-example5"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Is Bríd the teacher?]
      when "Table7A-example6"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Is it long until he arrives?]
      when "Table7A-example7"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Isn&rsquo;t Seán the teacher?]
      when "Table7A-example8"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Isn&rsquo;t Siobhán going to be there tomorrow?]
      when "Positive"
        | Positive
      when "Negative"
        | Negative
      when "Interrogative"
        | Interrogative
      when "7-2-1-B-title"
        | The Past Tense, the Past Habitual Tense and the Conditional Mood
      when "7-2-1-B-p1"
        | Lenition follows with the forms of the copula in the past tense, the past habitual tense and the conditional mood. #[i ba] or #[i b&rsquo;] is used in the past tense, past habitual tense or conditional mood as follows:
      when "7-2-1-B-a-p"
        | #[i ba] is always placed before #[i fh-] + #[i consonant], e.g., #[i Ba mhúinteoir lách é] #[+tl He was a pleasant teacher]; #[i Ba fhreagra cruinn é] #[+tl It was an accurate answer].
      when "7-2-1-B-b-p"
        | #[i ba] is placed before #[i fh-] + #[i vowel] in the following contexts:
      when "7-2-1-B-b-i-p"
        | the pronominals #[i é], #[i í], #[i ea], #[i éard], #[i eisean], #[i ise], #[i iad] and #[i iadsan], e.g., #[i Ba iad a bhuaigh an corn] #[+tl They were the ones who won the cup];
      when "7-2-1-B-b-ii-p"
        | prepositions, e.g., #[i Ba ar theacht i bhfeidhm an Achta a tharla sé] #[+tl It was on the coming into effect of the Act that it happened];
      when "7-2-1-B-b-iii-p"
        | prepositional pronominals, e.g., #[i Ba ann a bhí sé] #[+tl It was there that he was];
      when "7-2-1-B-b-iv-p"
        | adverbs that are not adjectival adverbs, e.g., #[i Ba arú inné a d&rsquo;ith siad an cáca] #[+tl It was the day before yesterday that they ate the cake].
      when "7-2-1-B-c-p"
        | #[i b&rsquo;] is placed before a vowel or before #[i fh-] + #[i vowel] in the following contexts:
      when "7-2-1-B-c-i-p"
        | nouns, e.g., #[i B&rsquo;innealtóir maith í] #[+tl She was a good engineer];
      when "7-2-1-B-c-ii-p"
        | adjectives, e.g., #[i B&rsquo;fhearúil an duine é] #[+tl He was a manly person];
      when "7-2-1-B-c-iii-p"
        | the demonstrative pronominals #[i eo], #[i in] and #[i iúd], e.g., #[i B&rsquo;in é é] #[+tl It was he]; #[i B&rsquo;eo amach é] #[+tl It was he who went out].
      when "7-2-1-B-c-iv-p"
        | adjectival adverbs, e.g., #[i B&rsquo;annamh a dhéanadh sé é] #[+tl It was rarely that he did it].
      when "7-2-1-B-d-p"
        | The forms #[i ba] or #[i ab] are allowed to be used before the neuter pronominal #[i ea] in the middle of a sentence that is in the past tense, the past habitual tense or the conditional mood, e.g., #[i Saighdiúirí ab ea iad] or #[i Saighdiúirí ba ea iad] (#[b EN]: both #[i They were soldiers]).
      when "7-2-1-B-p2"
        | The table below shows the positive form of the copula in a main clause that is in the past tense, the past habitual tense or the conditional mood.
      when "Table7B-header"
        | The Past Tense, Past Habitual Tense and Conditional Mood &mdash; Positive
      when "Table7B-caption"
        | Simple Forms in Main Clauses &mdash; The Past Tense, Past Habitual Tense and Conditional Mood &mdash; Positive Form
      when "Table7B-ba-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i I wanted to speak.]
      when "Table7B-ba-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i They were very generous with me.]
      when "Table7B-ba-example3"
        | #[b EN]: #[i It would have been a little help to me if I had gotten it in time.]
      when "Table7B-b-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i The picture would be beautiful if that hole weren&rsquo;t in the background.]
      when "Table7B-b-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i We would love to be listening to him every night.]
      when "Table7B-b-example3"
        | #[b EN]: #[i We knew that she would go nearby when it was dry.]
      when "Table7B-ba-ab-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i The Secretary would be the one to correct it in that case.]
      when "Table7B-ba-ab-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i She was a good leader.]
      when "Table7B-ba-ab-example3"
        | #[b EN]: #[i She was the one who was right.]
      when "Table7B-ba-ab-example4"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He was from Galway.]
      when "Table7B-ba-ab-example5"
        | #[b EN]: #[i She was from Dublin.]
      when "BeforeConsonant"
        | before a consonant
      when "BeforeConsonantQualified"
        | before a consonant or before #[i fh-] + #[i consonant]
      when "BeforeVowel"
        | before a vowel
      when "BeforeVowelQualified"
        | before a vowel or before #[i fh-] + #[i vowel]
      when "BeforeConsonantAndVowel"
        | before every consonant and every vowel
      when "7-2-1-B-p3"
        | The table below shows the negative form, the positive interrogative form and the negative interrogative form of the copula in a main clause that is in the past tense, the past habitual tense or the conditional mood.
      when "Table7C-caption"
        | Simple Forms in Main Clauses &mdash; The Past Tense, Past Habitual Tense and Conditional Mood &mdash; The Negative Form and The Interrogative Form
      when "Table7C-header"
        | The Past Tense, Past Habitual Tense and Conditional Mood
      when "Table7C-Níor-example"
        | #[b EN]: #[i She wouldn&rsquo;t like that to happen.]
      when "Table7C-Níorbh-example"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He was not to be imposed upon.]
      when "Table7C-Ar-example"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Was it difficult for you?]
      when "Table7C-Arbh-example"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Would it be better as it is?]
      when "Table7C-Nár-example"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He wouldn&rsquo;t dare to do it!]
      when "Table7C-Nárbh-example"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Wouldn&rsquo;t it be the devil?]
      when "7-2-2-title"
        | Simple Forms at the beginning of Subordinate Clauses, other than a Relative Clause
      when "7-2-2-A-title"
        | The Present Tense and Future Tense
      when "7-2-2-A-p1"
        | #[i gur] or #[i gurb] is used in the present or future tense as follows:
      when "7-2-2-A-a-p"
        | #[i gur] is always placed before a consonant, e.g., #[i Is dóigh leo gur teagascóir gairmiúil é Cian].
      when "7-2-2-A-b-p"
        | #[i gur] is placed before a vowel in the following contexts:
      when "7-2-2-A-b-i-p"
        | nouns (other than nouns in prepositional copula phrases mentioned under #[i gurb] below), e.g., #[i Is dóigh liom gur áit dheas an t&#x2011;óstán sin] #[+tl I hope that that hotel is a nice place]; #[i Síleann an tAire gur acmhainn theoranta an ciste sin] #[+tl The Minister thinks that that fund is a limited resource]; #[i Dúirt sí gur oifigeach maith é] #[+tl She said that he is a good officer].
      when "7-2-2-A-b-ii-p"
        | prepositions, e.g., #[i Deir sí gur ag an rince a bheidh sí] #[+tl She says that she will be at the dance].
      when "7-2-2-A-b-iii-p"
        | prepositional pronominals, e.g., #[i Dúradh liom gur uait a tháinig an leabhar sin] #[+tl I was told that the book came from you].
      when "7-2-2-A-b-iv-p"
        | adverbs (other than #[i amhlaidh] #[+tl as such]) which are not adjectival adverbs, e.g., #[i Síltear gur amach anseo atá i gceist] #[+tl It is thought that it is in the future]; #[i Tuigtear dom gur amuigh sa ghairdín atá an ceiliúradh ar bun] #[+tl It is understood by me that the celebration is taking place in the garden].
      when "7-2-2-A-b-v-p"
        | the pronominals #[i é], #[i í], #[i eisean], #[i ise], #[i iad] and #[i iadsan] if the pronominal is the agent or object of a verbal noun, e.g., #[i Síleann sí gur #[+underline é a bhailiú] is fearr] #[+tl She thinks that it is better to collect it]; #[i Dar leis gur #[+underline iad a fhoilsiú] is fearr] #[+tl He thinks that it is better to publish them].
      when "7-2-2-A-c-p"
        | #[i gurb] is placed before a vowel in the following contexts:
      when "7-2-2-A-c-i-p"
        | adjectives, e.g., #[i Sílim gurb iontach an deis duit é] #[+tl I think that it is a wonderful opportunity for you]; #[i Ceapaim gurb eolach an bhean í] #[+tl I think that the woman is knowledgeable];
      when "7-2-2-A-c-ii-p"
        | #[i amhlaidh (gurb amhlaidh)], or adjectival adverbs (#[i go hard], #[i gurb ard]; #[i go hannamh], #[i gurb annamh]), e.g., #[i Measaim gurb amhlaidh atá] #[+tl I consider that it is like that]; #[i Sílim gurb annamh a tharlaíonn a leithéid] #[+tl I think that such a thing happens rarely];
      when "7-2-2-A-c-iii-p"
        | the pronominals #[i é], #[i í], #[i ea], #[i eisean], #[i ise], #[i iad] and #[i iadsan] when the pronominal is neither the agent nor the object of the verb noun, e.g., #[i Deir sí gurb í a hiníon í] #[+tl She says that it is her daughter]; #[i Dar le hAoife gurb eisean a rinne é] #[+tl Aoife says that he is the one who did it]; #[i Dúirt sise gurb é Sorcha an t&#x2011;ainm a bhí uirthi féin] #[+tl She said that her name was Sorcha]; #[i D&rsquo;admhaigh sí gurb í féin a rinne é] #[+tl She admitted that she herself did it];
      when "7-2-2-A-c-iv-p"
        | the demonstrative pronominals #[i eo], #[i in] and #[i iúd], e.g., #[i Deir sí gurb in é an fear] #[+tl She says that it is the man];
      when "7-2-2-A-c-v-p"
        | the following prepositional copular phrases: #[i acmhainn do] #[+tl ability to], #[i áil le] #[+tl desire to], #[i aitheanta do] #[+tl known to], #[i aithnid do] #[+tl acquainted with], #[i eagal do/le] #[+tl fear of/by], #[i éadáil le] #[+tl benefit to], #[i ealaín do] #[+tl art of], #[i éigean do] #[+tl necessity for], #[i eol do] #[+tl knowledge of], #[i oircheas do] #[+tl proper to], e.g., #[i Dar leo gurb acmhainn dóibh teach a cheannach] #[+tl They say that they have the ability to buy a house];
      when "7-2-2-A-c-vi-p"
        | these particular words: #[i áibhéil] #[+tl exaggeration], #[i éard] #[+tl the one that], #[i ionadh] #[+tl surprise], #[i iontas] #[+tl astonishment] and #[i ualach] #[+tl burden], e.g., #[i Dúirt sé liom gurb ionadh leis an ní a tharla] #[+tl He told me that he was surprised by what happened].
      when "7-2-2-A-p2"
        | In the following table, the positive and negative forms of copula are given at the beginning of a subordinate clause (other than a relative clause) that is in the present tense or the future tense.
      when "Table7D-header"
        | The Present Tense and Future Tense
      when "Table7D-caption"
        | Simple Forms at the beginning of Subordinate Clauses, other than Relative Clauses &mdash; Present and Future Tense
      when "Table7D-gur-cons-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i They think #[b that] Seán is a good teacher.]
      when "Table7D-gur-cons-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i I think #[b that] the meeting will be in the afternoon tomorrow.]
      when "Table7D-gur-vow-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i They think #[b that] he is a nurse.]
      when "Table7D-gur-vow-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i I think #[b that] they will win.]
      when "Table7D-gurb-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He thinks #[b that] it is a beautiful day.]
      when "Table7D-gurb-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i I don&rsquo;t think #[b that] they are the same.]
      when "Table7D-gurb-example3"
        | #[b EN]: #[i It is necessary #[b that] they have the ability.]
      when "Table7D-gurb-example4"
        | #[b EN]: #[i If it is necessary #[b that] they do it.]
      when "Table7D-nach-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He says #[b that] the game will be played tomorrow.]
      when "Table7D-nach-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i We understand #[b that] it is not the end of the world if we lose.]
      when "Table7D-nach-example3"
        | #[b EN]: #[i They think #[b that] he is not a good researcher.]
      when "Table7D-nach-example4"
        | #[b EN]: #[i I think #[b that] it is not a safe harbor.]
      when "7-2-2-B-title"
        | The Past Tense, the Past Habitual Tense and the Conditional Mood
      when "7-2-2-B-p"
        | Lenition follows with the forms of the copula in the past tense, the past habitual tense and the conditional mood. There is an option for the positive forms &mdash; see #[+link("#sec_7_2_2_B_a", "(a)")] and #[+link("#sec_7_2_2_B_b", "(b)")] below.
      when "7-2-2-B-a-title"
        | #[i gur] or #[i gurbh]
      when "7-2-2-B-a-p1"
        | The positive forms #[i gur] or #[i gurbh] are used in the past tense, the past habitual tense or the conditional mood as follows:
      when "7-2-2-B-a-i"
        | #[i gur] is placed before a consonant or before #[i fh-] + #[i consonant] in all situations, e.g., #[i D&rsquo;ainneoin an méid a d&rsquo;impigh sí air, níor dhóigh leis gur chóir an madra a choinneáil] #[+tl Despite all she asked of him, he did not think it was right to keep the dog].
      when "7-2-2-B-a-ii"
        | #[i gurbh] is placed before a vowel or before #[i fh-] + #[i vowel] in all situations, e.g., #[i Creidtear gurbh ealaíontóir cumasach ab ea é] #[+tl It is believed that he was a talented artist]; #[i Dúirt sé gurbh iomaí cleas glic a d&rsquo;imir Seán air] #[+tl He said that Seán played many clever tricks on him].
      when "7-2-2-B-a-p2"
        | The table below lays out the positive form of the copula in a main clause that is in the past tense, the past habitual tense or the conditional mood.
      when "Table7E-header"
        | The Past Tense, Past Habitual Tense and Conditional Mood
      when "Table7E-caption"
        | Simple Forms at the beginning of Subordinate Clauses, except Relative Clauses &mdash; Past Tense, Past Habitual Tense and Conditional Mood &mdash; #[i gur] and #[i gurbh]
      when "Table7E-gur-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i Eoin said #[b that] it was right to sell it.]
      when "Table7E-gur-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i We thought #[b that] he was the most generous person.]
      when "Table7E-gurbh-example1"
        | #[b EN]: #[i He confirmed #[b that] he was bankrupt.]
      when "Table7E-gurbh-example2"
        | #[b EN]: #[i She said #[b that] it was for the public good.]
      when "7-2-2-B-b-title"
        | #[i go mba] or #[i go mb&rsquo;]
      when "7-2-2-B-b-p1"
        | It is also optional to use the positive forms #[i go mba] or #[i go mb&rsquo;] in the past tense, the past habitual tense or the conditional mood as follows:
      when "7-2-2-B-b-i"
        | #[i go mba] is placed before a consonant or before #[i fh-] + #[i consonant] in all situations, e.g., #[i Cé gur impigh sí air, níor dhóigh leis go mba chóir an madra a choinneáil] #[+tl Although she begged him, he did not think it right to keep the dog].
      when "7-2-2-B-b-ii"
        | #[i go mba] is placed before a vowel or before #[i fh-] + #[i vowel] in the following contexts:
      when "7-2-2-B-b-ii-1"
